11.body: Input and Output (I/O) On terminal (standard in, standard out) Standard out example: ls Standard in (and out) example: jshell Java I/O functions: IO.readln(prompt) IO.println(message) IO.print(message) Store input in variables Write a program that repeats user input
11.title: I/O

12.body: Challenging to think about programs: What goes in your code? What does the computer do for you? What information does the user provide? Common mistake: writing user input in your code Three roles to consider: Programmers write instructions Computers follow instructions Users break things provide input To write good instructions, you need to think about how the computer will follow them and how the user will interact with your program. However, none of that actually goes in your code!

12.title: The Program, Computer, and User

13.body: Computers are complicated. How do we understand what they're doing? What can we do that's similar to the following: IO.println IO.readln var x = ... x = ... Easier to understand programs if you can imagine how you would execute their instructions.

14.body: Write a hello world program from scratch. Don't look at any code, but feel free to check your notes if you forgot how to do something. Experiement with the Greeting.java program and find an answer to each of the questions in the comments. Update the Home.java program so that it works for everyone in this classroom. You're only allowed five lines of code inside the main function: the four printlns and one variable. Hint: you need to read user input. Finish the Email.java program.

8.body: Text files vs binary files Source code goes in text files (.java), compiling code creates binary files (.class) More Windows bashing: .java.txt Windows is fine, I'm just a hater Plaintext files have many file extensions File extensions are just hints Markdown Plaintext with simple rules for markup My notes and websites use markdown Easy to render to pdf or convert to other markup languages (html, latex)

9.body: Hello World: compact source vs standard Java structure We're only using compact source in lecture Requires --enable-preview in Java 24 Allowed by default in Java 25 Explain parts of program: main(): function, entry point void: keyword, return type {}: code block IO: namespacing println(): function "Hello World": strings
